  {
    "slug": "what-is-a-demand-coop",
    "title": "What is a Demand Coop",
    "description": "A co-op is an economic system built on the simple idea that coordinating the economic activity of individuals can allow them to access benefits normally reserved for large economi...",
    "excerpt": "A co-op is an economic system built on the simple idea that coordinating the economic activity of individuals can allow them to access benefits normally reserved for large economi...",
    "publishedAt": "2026-05-19",
    "updatedAt": "2026-05-20",
    "author": "Deon Robinson",
    "category": "Technology",
    "readingTime": "3 min read",
    "image": "/placeholder.jpg",
    "imageAlt": "Cahootz blog post image.",
    "featured": false,
    "tags": [],
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A co-op is an economic system built on the simple idea that coordinating the economic activity of individuals can allow them to access benefits normally reserved for large economic entities like businesses, financial institutions, and governments. Most co-ops organize around labor — asking how workers can leverage their labor for better economic outcomes. Cahootz is a network of co-ops asking a fundamentally different question. Because globalization, technology, and digital communication have made labor cheaper and more accessible across the world, what happens if a community organizes its demand instead of just its labor?"
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "A demand co-op is a cooperative that pools and directs the spending power of its members. Demand determines what gets built, who survives, and where wealth flows. Most communities already have enormous spending power, but because that demand is unorganized, the value created from it is captured by outside businesses and investors. A demand co-op coordinates that spending so economic activity can build communal businesses, assets, and long-term ownership instead of constant leakage."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "What does this look like in practice? Imagine the co-op owns a grocery store. Each purchase is lightly taxed and placed into a treasury. One day, a member creates a proposal to build a delivery service. The co-op funds it, helps operate it, and partially owns the new business. In turn, the business hires co-op members, maintains fair pricing, and provides services to the community. Those workers and businesses then spend more money within the co-op network. The treasury accumulates more assets, those assets generate proportional yield, and economic leakage is reduced over time."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "This model makes some bold assumptions about whether people can cooperate at scale outside of corporate or government structures, and whether personal self-interest or ideological capture will eventually overpower the system. These concerns are valid. Most economic systems fail not because people lack resources, but because coordination, trust, and long-term incentives break down over time. In many existing demand cooperatives, such as rotating savings groups, there is often a trusted central coordinator — frequently an older community member — who helps maintain accountability and keep the interests of the group aligned."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "This is a real challenge, and one we will address more deeply in future articles. But we believe communities may be able to align around shared goals and trusted systems that help ensure participants act in the long-term interests of the group rather than short-term individual extraction."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The future may belong to communities that can organize capital, trust, and demand faster than traditional institutions. Cahootz is our attempt to build the scaffolding."
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "If you want to be cahootz signup for one of coop or petition to start your own."
      }
    ]
  }
